## Security & Error Handling Review — `app.js`

### 🔴 Critical Issues

#### 1. No Body Parsing / Request Size Limits
There's no `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()` middleware, and no payload size cap. Without a size limit, the server is vulnerable to **denial-of-service via oversized request bodies**.

```js
// Add before your routes
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

#### 2. Missing Security Headers (`helmet`)
Without security headers, the app is vulnerable to clickjacking, MIME-type sniffing, and cross-site scripting. Use [`helmet`](https://helmetjs.github.io/) to set safe defaults:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // Sets X-Frame-Options, CSP, HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.
```

#### 3. No Global Error Handler
Unhandled route errors will fall through to Express's default error handler, which **leaks stack traces in development** and may expose internals in production:

```js
// Add at the end, after all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack); // Log internally, never send to client
  const status = err.status || 500;
  res.status(status).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'An unexpected error occurred'
      : err.message,
  });
});
```

---

### 🟠 Moderate Issues

#### 4. No 404 Handler for Unknown Routes
Express will return a verbose HTML response for unknown routes, leaking server info:

```js
// Add before the error handler
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});
```

#### 5. No Rate Limiting
The API has no rate limiting, making it susceptible to brute-force and DoS attacks. Use [`express-rate-limit`](https://github.com/express-rate-limit/express-rate-limit):

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // limit each IP to 100 requests per window
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});
app.use(limiter);
```

#### 6. Hardcoded Port
Port `3000` is hardcoded. Use an environment variable so it can be configured per-environment without code changes:

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
```

---

### 🟡 Minor / Best Practice Issues

#### 7. No CORS Policy
Without explicit CORS config, cross-origin behavior is undefined. Use the [`cors`](https://github.com/expressjs/cors) package to define an explicit allowlist:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(',') || false }));
