### 1. Missing Request Body Parsing Middleware
The app has no middleware to parse incoming JSON or URL-encoded bodies. Any `POST`/`PUT` routes added later will silently fail to parse request data.

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' })); // Limit body size to prevent DoS
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

---

### 2. No Security Headers
Missing HTTP security headers leave the app vulnerable to common attacks (clickjacking, MIME sniffing, XSS, etc.). Use the `helmet` package:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

This sets headers like `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, and more.

---

### 3. No Rate Limiting
The `/users` endpoint (and others) are wide open to abuse. Add rate limiting:

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // limit each IP to 100 requests per window
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});
app.use(limiter);
```

---

### 4. No Global Error Handler
Unhandled errors will expose stack traces (leaking internal implementation details). Add a centralized error handler:

```js
// 404 handler
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
});

// Global error handler (must have 4 params)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack); // Log internally, don't expose to client
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'Internal Server Error'
      : err.message,
  });
});
```

---

### 5. `/health` Endpoint Leaks Precise Timestamps
Returning a precise server timestamp is a minor info-disclosure risk (fingerprinting, timing attacks). Consider omitting it or using a coarser value:

```js
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok' }); // Remove timestamp, or use a rounded value
});
```

---

### 6. Hardcoded Port
Port `3000` is hardcoded. Use an environment variable to avoid conflicts and improve configurability:

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

---

### 7. No CORS Policy
Without explicit CORS configuration, cross-origin behavior is undefined. Explicitly configure it:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGIN || 'https://yourdomain.com',
  methods: ['GET'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
}));
```

