  const page = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.page, 10) || 1);
  const limit = Math.min(100, Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.limit, 10) || 20));
  // ... fetch paginated, sanitized data
});
```

---

### 7. 🔒 Port Should Be Configurable via Environment Variable
Hard-coding port `3000` is a minor but real concern — it should come from the environment so secrets/config aren't embedded in code:

```js
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT, 10) || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
```

---

### 8. 🐛 No CORS Configuration
If this API is consumed by a browser, you need an explicit CORS policy — otherwise you're either blocking legitimate clients or (if you add `cors()` naively) allowing all origins:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGIN || 'https://yourdomain.com',
  methods: ['GET'],
}));
```

---

